Bend it like Beckham¶

by Will Nguyen

Introduction¶

Odell Cornelious Beckham Jr. (OBJ) was drafted by the New York Giants 12th overall in the 2014 NFL draft from LSU. Famous for his one-handed touchdown catch against the Dallas Cowboys, Odell had a phenomenal debut season setting NFL records on his way to a 2014 Offensive Rookie of the Year award. After 5 years with the Giants, Odell briefly played with the Cleveland Browns before winning a Super Bowl with the LA Rams. He is now on the Baltimore Ravens after recovering from an ACL injury.

But just how good was Odell as a New York Giant?

This statistical analysis will focus on comparing Odell's performances as a wide receiver since entering the league and until he left New York. I will be focusing this analysis on WR metrics relating to recieving yards, receptions, and touchdowns.

I will be using Python to scrape, clean, and analyze wide receiver statistics from 2014 through 2018. All data is from pro-football-reference.com.

Standard importing of necessary/used libraries for scraping, storing, manipulating, and plottig the data.

Source¶

This project utilizes data from pro-football-reference. Because the data we want is organized on their own page by year (and the url is non-encrypted), we can use loops to scrape the receiving data from 2014 through to 2018.

Even though there are a lot of stats that I don't need, I'll first scrape the entire page and put it into a table to filter later. I also added a column indicating the year that player's stats were recorded.

In [2]:
url = "https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/receiving.htm"
dfs = []

for i in range(2014, 2019):
    # pulls page and finds table with stats
    re = requests.get(url)
    root = BeautifulSoup(re.content)
    t = root.find("table")
    
    # convert to dataframe and show what year stats are from
    df = pd.read_html(str(t))[0]
    df["year"] = [i for k in range(0, df["GS"].count())]
    
    dfs.append(df)
    url = url.replace(str(i), str(i+1))

Data Filtering and Cleaning¶

Next steps are to filter out any unwanted data and clean up the data that what we do want. These include any rows such as repeating column headers and any non-wide receivers. Even though most of the 32 NFL teams typically run 2-3 WRs, I will be filtering for the top 32 WRs for each year, also known as each team's WR1. I am doing this for two reasons. First, because this analysis is focused on analyzing how succesful Odell Beckham was, it makes sense to compare him to other top receivers. Secondly, including every receiver for each year wouldn't provide any meaningful insight. It would just add more noise in the visualizations.

I also convert any data that appears to be a number, but is actually a string, and remove any unwanted columns before combining each of the yearly tables into a single table.

In [3]:
wr = []
for i in range(0, len(dfs)):
    df = dfs[i]
    # remove repeat column titles
    df = df[~df["Rk"].str.contains("Rk")]
    
    # filter for wrs
    df = df[df["Pos"]=="WR"]
    
    # filter for top 32 wrs (WR1)
    df["Rk"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Rk"])
    
    # convert from string to numbers
    df["TD"] = pd.to_numeric(df["TD"])
    df["Tgt"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Tgt"])
    df["Rec"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Rec"])
    df["Yds"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Yds"])
    df["Player"] = df["Player"].astype('string')
    
    df = df[df["Rk"] < 33]
    wr.append(df)
In [4]:
# combine tables from each year
table = wr[0]
for i in range(1, len(wr)):
    table = table.append(wr[i])
    
table = table[["Player", "GS", "Tgt", "Rec", "Ctch%", "Yds", "Y/R", "TD", "Y/Tgt", "R/G", "Y/G", "year"]]

Next steps are to calculate any desired metrics that weren't include from pro-football-reference.

In [5]:
names = []
catch = []
tar_g = []
rec_g = []
yrds_g = []
yrds_t = []
yrds_r = []

for x in table.itertuples():
    # remove Pro Bowl and AP indicators
    names.append(x[1].replace("*", "").replace("+", "").strip())
    
    # fix catch%
    catch.append(x[5].replace("%", ""))

    # convert other "per" metrics
    tar_g.append(int(x[3])/int(x[2]))
    rec_g.append(int(x[4])/int(x[2]))
    yrds_g.append(int(x[6])/int(x[2]))
    yrds_t.append(int(x[6])/int(x[3]))
    yrds_r.append(int(x[6])/int(x[4]))
    
table["Player"] = names
table["rec"] = x[4]
table["catch_rate"] = catch
table["tar/g"] = tar_g
table["rec/g"] = rec_g
table["yrds/g"] = yrds_g
table["yrds/t"] = yrds_t
table["yrds/r"] = yrds_r

table['catch_rate'] = table['catch_rate'].astype(float)/100
table.drop(['GS', 'Ctch%', 'rec','Y/R', 'Y/Tgt', 'R/G', 'Y/G'], axis=1, inplace = True)
table = table[[col for col in table if col not in ["year"]] + ["year"]]

Data Visualizations and Analysis¶

Now that we have our finished table, here is a breakdown of what data each column contains.

  1. Player: player's name
  2. tar: "targets", number of times targeted with a pass
  3. rec: "receptions", number of catches
  4. yrds: "yards", number of receving yards
  5. td: "touchdowns", number of touchdown receptions made
  6. catch_rate: percentage of targets caught
  7. tar/g: "targets per game"
  8. rec/g: "receptions per game"
  9. yrds/g: "yards per game"
  10. yrds/t: "yards per target"
  11. yrds/r: "yards per reception"
  12. year: year stats were recorded

Now, lets look at some graphs to get an idea of how Odell fares amongst the top receivers each year, starting with yrds/g vs rec/g.

Odell spent most of 2017 injured, playing 4 games and started 2.

In [11]:
plt.subplots(figsize = (12, 8))

i = 2014
for y in table["year"].unique(): 
    year = table[(table==y).any(axis=1)]
    year = year[~year["Player"].str.contains("Odell Beckham Jr.")]
    
    plt.scatter(marker="x", x=year["rec/g"], y=year["yrds/g"], label=str(i))
    i+=1
    
plt.legend()
    
for x in table.itertuples():
    name = x[1]
    # (y) yards per game [9] vs (x) receptions per game [8]
    yrds_g = x[9]
    rec_g = x[8]
    if(name == "Odell Beckham Jr."):
        plt.scatter(marker="o", x=x[8], y=x[9])
        plt.annotate(str(x[12]) + " " + x[1], (x[8], x[9]))
            
yrds_reg = np.array(table["yrds/g"]).reshape(-1, 1)
rec_reg = np.array(table["rec/g"]).reshape(-1, 1)

reg = LinearRegression().fit(rec_reg, yrds_reg)
plt.plot(rec_reg, reg.intercept_ + reg.coef_ * rec_reg, '-')

x = "rec_g"
y = "yrds_g"
plt.xlabel(x)
plt.ylabel(y)
plt.title(y + " vs. " + x)
plt.show()

This chart provides insights into the efficiency of the receiver by showing how many yards they gain on average for each reception.

As you can see, Odell consistently performed above average in terms of yrds/g vs rec/g, with 2014 being his best performance in this metric.

So just how good was Odell as a New York Giant?¶

Outside of his 2017 season, Odell was pretty good as a Giant. His 2018 season was right around average, but keep in mind he was coming back from an ACL injury and he's being compared to the top 32 receivers in the league, but overall he was consistently above average. Odell only underperformed in terms of overall receptions vs targets. But his receptions vs targets per game average is amongst the very best in the NFL.

So to recap, from 2014-2018 Odell had:

  • 581 Targets (8th)
  • 365 Receptions (7th)
  • 41 Touchdowns (3rd)
  • 5,174 Receiving Yards (4th)
  • 388 Yards per Game (5th)

All while dealing with an ACL tear and missing 13 games. That is not even to take account how poor the Giants' overall performance during that time period was. He also finished with 90+ receptions in 3/4 seasons, 1,000+ receiving yards in all 4, and 10+ touchdowns in 3/4 seasons.

Of course there are other factors to consider when analyzing a wide receiver's performance. But the numbers alone suggest Odell Beckham Jr. was a very good receiver with the Giants.
